---
import { Container, TextSection, Button } from '@components/odyssey-theme';
import Layout from '../layouts/Page.astro';

const seo = {
	title: 'Context | NMES for Astronauts',
	description: 'Etiology and Affected Demographic of Muscle Degradation in Space',
};
---

<style>
  .icon-header {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    margin-right: 0.5rem;
    vertical-align: middle;
    color: var(--theme-primary);
  }
	img {
		max-width: 100%;
		border-radius: var(--theme-shape-radius);
	}
  .nav-button-container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    transform: scale(1.2);
  }
</style>

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <Container>
    <TextSection narrow>
      <h1 style="text-align: center;">The Context: Muscle Atrophy in Space</h1>
      
      <h3>Who is at Risk?</h3>
      <p>
        Every astronaut on a long-duration mission faces this challenge. Whether it's a 6-month stay on the ISS or a 3-year journey to Mars, the human body adapts to its environmentâ€”often in ways we don't want.
      </p>
      <p>
        Astronauts face a unique challenge: <strong>microgravity</strong>. On Earth, our muscles are constantly working against gravity to support our weight and move us around. In space, this load disappears.
      </p>
      <p>
        Without gravity pulling on them, muscles begin to weaken immediately. This isn't just about strength; it's about safety. A weakened crew member might struggle with emergency procedures or be unable to walk upon returning to Earth (or landing on Mars).
      </p>
      
      <h3>Why Does It Happen?</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Use it or lose it.</strong> On Earth, just standing up requires your "anti-gravity" muscles (legs and spine) to work against 1G of force. In space, that load disappears.
      </p>
      <p>
        The body, being efficient, stops maintaining muscle it doesn't need. The result? Up to <strong>30% muscle mass loss</strong> in just six months. Bones also become brittle, increasing fracture risk.
      </p>
      <div class="nav-button-container">
        <Button href="/countermeasures" customIcon>
          Next: The Solutions
          <Fragment slot="icon">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" style="width: 24px; height: 24px;">
              <line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line>
              <polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline>
            </svg>
          </Fragment>
        </Button>
      </div>
    </TextSection>
  </Container>
</Layout>
